  "datePublished": "2026-03-05",
  "description": "A vector space is a collection of objects — called vectors — that can be added together and scaled by numbers from a field, in a way that behaves the way addition and scaling ought to behave. The field supplies the scalars: these might be the real numbers, the complex numbers, or any other field. The vectors themselves might be arrows in space, columns of numbers, functions, polynomials, or any of a hundred other things. What makes them a vector space is not what they are, but how they combine.\n",
  "name": "Vector Space",
